    public class Rule
extends DLPElementAdapter
implements Comparable<Rule>, DLPElement, net.sf.tweety.commons.util.rules.Rule<DLPHead,DLPElement>
    This class models a rule for a disjunctive logic program. A rule is a collection of literals and more sophisticated rule elements like Aggregate or Arithmetic. It uses separate lists for the head and the body. It also implements the Comparable interface to allow the ordering in collections.
    Author:
    Tim Janus, Thomas Vengels

      • isSafe

        public boolean isSafe()
        Proofs if the given rule is safe for use in a solver. To get a felling when a rule is safe read the following text from the dlv documentation: A variable X in an aggregate-free rule is safe if at least one of the following conditions is satisfied: X occurs in a positive standard predicate in the body of the rule; X occurs in a true negated standard predicate in the body of the rule; X occurs in the last argument of an arithmetic predicate A and all other arguments of A are safe. (*not supported yet) A rule is safe if all its variables are safe. However, cyclic dependencies are disallowed, e.g., :- #succ(X,Y), #succ(Y,X) is not safe.
        Returns:
        true if the rule is safe considering the above conditions, false otherwise.
